== Types == Although similar in appearance to {{ill|Dōsojin|ja|道祖神|12=draft}}, Ōban Shin can be identified by the following characteristics:
# '''Inscribed Ōban Shin''' #: A stone monument inscribed with Chinese or Sanskrit characters related to Rāhu (Ōban). # '''Snake-Headed Ōban Shin''' #: Depicted with an expression of wrath similar to {{ill|Fudō Myō-ō|ja|不動明王|12=draft}}, often featuring nine snake heads symbolizing Rāhu. # '''Sun and Moon Ōban Shin''' #: Features depictions or inscriptions of the sun and moon on either side or above and below Ōban Shin, reflecting attributes inherited from Susanoo. # '''Solar or Lunar Eclipse Ōban Shin''' #: Depicted with black circles (or partially black circles) symbolizing solar or lunar eclipses, representing Rāhu’s role in causing such phenomena. # '''Serpentine Ōban Shin''' #: Completely depicted as a serpent, representing either Rāhu’s original form or its other half, {{ill|Ketu|ja|ケートゥ|12=draft}}. # '''Composite Ōban Shin''' #: Combines elements from the above types. == See Also == * {{ill|Nine Celestial Luminaries|ja|九曜|12=draft}} * {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|スサノオ|12=draft}} * {{ill|Rāhu|ja|ラーフ|12=draft}} * {{ill|Ketu|ja|ケートゥ|12=draft}} * {{ill|List of Japanese deities|ja|日本の神の一覧|12=draft}}
