[[File:God of Ooban.png|thumb|right|170px|Ōban Shin]]
'''Ōban Shin''' (黄幡神, おうばんしん) is a deity worshipped as part of the {{ill|Nine Celestial Luminaries|ja|九曜|12=draft|12=draft}} and represents {{ill|Rāhu|ja|羅睺|12=draft|12=draft}}. This deity is typically enshrined in the form of stone monuments at village boundaries, within villages, or at the intersections of roads and three-way junctions.

While currently revered as a protective deity akin to {{ill|Dōsojin|ja|道祖神|12=draft|12=draft}}, Ōban Shin originated from {{ill|Rāhu (mythology)|ja|ラーフ|12=draft|12=draft}}, an {{ill|Asura|ja|アスラ|12=draft|12=draft}} from Indian mythology, feared as a bringer of disasters. After being introduced to Japan, Rāhu was syncretized with {{ill|Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|スサノオ|12=draft|12=draft}}, a deity associated with causing solar eclipses.

Ōban Shin is also one of the {{ill|Eight Guardian Deities|ja|八将神|1=Eight Directional Deities|12=draft|12=draft}}, known as the "Tomb of All Things" or the "God of Warfare." It is considered inauspicious to move soil in the direction of this deity's presence but auspicious for matters related to martial arts.

As a result of syncretism, Ōban Shin was classified as a deity but maintains deep ties with Buddhism, particularly {{ill|Esoteric Buddhism|ja|密教|12=draft|12=draft}}. In Buddhism, its {{ill|honji suijaku|ja|本地垂迹|12=draft|12=draft}} is identified with {{ill|Marici|ja|摩利支天|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Types ==
Although similar in appearance to {{ill|Dōsojin|ja|道祖神|12=draft|12=draft}}, Ōban Shin can be identified by the following characteristics:

# '''Inscribed Ōban Shin'''
#: A stone monument inscribed with Chinese or Sanskrit characters related to Rāhu (Ōban).
# '''Snake-Headed Ōban Shin'''
#: Depicted with an expression of wrath similar to {{ill|Fudō Myō-ō|ja|不動明王|12=draft|12=draft}}, often featuring nine snake heads symbolizing Rāhu.
# '''Sun and Moon Ōban Shin'''
#: Features depictions or inscriptions of the sun and moon on either side or above and below Ōban Shin, reflecting attributes inherited from Susanoo.
# '''Solar or Lunar Eclipse Ōban Shin'''
#: Depicted with black circles (or partially black circles) symbolizing solar or lunar eclipses, representing Rāhu’s role in causing such phenomena.
# '''Serpentine Ōban Shin'''
#: Completely depicted as a serpent, representing either Rāhu’s original form or its other half, {{ill|Ketu|ja|ケートゥ|12=draft|12=draft}}.
# '''Composite Ōban Shin'''
#: Combines elements from the above types.
